# Item List App (Angular)

A minimal Angular example demonstrating a component + service pair, following
current Angular best practices (standalone components, typed models, RxJS
Observables, and explicit loading/error/empty states).

## Structure

```
src/app/
├── models/
│   └── item.model.ts          # Item interface (id, name, description)
├── services/
│   └── item.service.ts        # ItemService.getItems() -> Observable<Item[]>
├── item-list/
│   ├── item-list.component.ts
│   ├── item-list.component.html
│   └── item-list.component.css
└── app.component.ts            # Hosts <app-item-list>
```

## Design notes

- **Standalone components** are used (no `NgModule` boilerplate needed), which
  is the current Angular-recommended default.
- **ItemService** is `providedIn: 'root'`, so it's a singleton available via
  DI without needing to register it in a module.
- **Separation of concerns**: the service owns data access; the component
  owns presentation and UI state (loading / error / empty / loaded).
- **Error handling**: `getItems()` returns an Observable that can error; the
  component's `subscribe({ next, error })` handles both paths and exposes a
  user-facing retry button. Flip `simulateError` to `true` in
  `item.service.ts` to see the error state.
- **Performance**: `trackBy` is used on `*ngFor` to avoid unnecessary
  re-renders when item identity hasn't changed.
- In a real app, `ItemService` would inject `HttpClient` and call a real API
  endpoint instead of returning mock data.

## Running locally

This snippet assumes it's dropped into a project generated by:

```bash
ng new item-list-app --standalone
cd item-list-app
ng serve
```

Then copy these files into the matching paths under `src/app/`.

## Publishing to GitHub

1. `git init` (if not already a repo)
2. `git add .`
3. `git commit -m "Add ItemList component and ItemService"`
4. Create an empty repository on GitHub (e.g. `item-list-app`)
5. `git remote add origin https://github.com/<your-username>/item-list-app.git`
6. `git push -u origin main`
